AirportFaster — Development Sprint Plan

Version: 1.0 · Last updated: 2026-05-14 · Status: Draft for founder review

Document Purpose

This plan turns the MVP scope into an ordered, sprint-by-sprint delivery sequence. It assumes a small senior team (or AI agents operating as one) and two-week sprints. The goal is a revenue-generating MVP: a customer can search, book, and pay for an airport service, and the admin team can run operations — all without developer intervention to launch a new airport.

Guiding sequencing logic: foundation → revenue path → operational control → growth engine. Nothing fake ships in production flows; every sprint ends with working, tested, documented software.

⸻

Sprint 0 — Foundation (1 sprint)

Goal: a deployable skeleton with the architecture decided in AGENTS.md.
- Monorepo setup: apps/web, packages/api (Fastify modular monolith), packages/db (Prisma), packages/shared, packages/jobs.
- PostgreSQL + Redis provisioned; dev/staging/prod environments; CI pipeline.
- Prisma schema from the Database Architecture doc — Identity & Access, Airports, Services domains first; migrations + seed (roles, permissions, 3 services, settings).
- Auth & RBAC module: staff login, sessions, role-permission enforcement middleware, audit_logs writing.
- Sentry + PostHog wired. .env.example complete.
Exit: a staff user can log in to an empty admin shell; CI is green; docs updated.

⸻

Sprint 1 — Dynamic Airports & CMS Core

Goal: admin can create and publish an airport with zero developer involvement.
- Airports module: CRUD, translations (en/ar), images (S3), airport_services join, status/publish.
- CMS/SEO core: airport_seo, page generation data model, content_approval_workflow.
- Admin dashboard: Airports module UI — add/edit airport, configure services per airport, SEO fields, preview, publish/unpublish.
- Public site: Next.js shell, dynamic airport landing page route (SSG + ISR), airports directory.
Exit: admin adds "Dubai International Airport", publishes it, and it appears live and indexable.

⸻

Sprint 2 — Pricing & Availability Engines

Goal: a published airport-service has a real, configurable price and availability.
- Pricing module: pricing_rules (both modes — fixed and cost+markup, D-008), currency_rates, rule precedence, quote function (pure, unit-tested).
- Availability module: availability_rules, blackout_dates, cut-off/min-notice logic, availability function.
- Admin UI: pricing setup and availability setup flows (per airport/service/supplier).
- Suppliers module (data layer): suppliers, coverage tables, supplier CRUD in admin.
Exit: a search query against an airport-service returns a correct price and availability status.

⸻

Sprint 3 — Search & Booking Flow (no payment yet)

Goal: the customer journey works end-to-end up to checkout.
- Search module: PostgreSQL full-text search, airport/service/IATA/city search, filters, availability- and pricing-aware results.
- Public site: homepage with hero search, search results, service selection, booking details form, review step.
- Bookings module: customers, bookings (Draft/Pending Payment), booking_passengers, booking_flights, booking_price_snapshots, booking_events/status_history.
Exit: a customer can search, pick a service, enter details, and reach a checkout page showing a snapshotted price.

⸻

Sprint 4 — Stripe Checkout & Payment (revenue goes live)

Goal: AirportFaster can take real money. This sprint makes the MVP monetisable.
- Payments module: Stripe Payment Intents, multi-currency checkout, charge at checkout (D-007).
- Stripe Webhooks module: signature validation, stripe_webhook_events persistence + idempotency, payment status driven by webhooks only.
- Booking lifecycle: Pending Payment → Paid → Pending Supplier Assignment; booking reference + secure manage_token.
- Confirmation page; booking_events timeline populated.
Exit: a customer completes a real payment; booking is marked Paid via verified webhook; appears in admin.

⸻

Sprint 5 — Operations: Bookings, Suppliers, Manual Assignment

Goal: the admin team can operate every booking.
- Admin dashboard: Bookings module (list, filters, detail, timeline, notes, status management); Overview page widgets.
- Manual supplier assignment: booking_supplier_assignments, assignment UI, status flow to Confirmed.
- Suppliers module UI: profiles, coverage, documents, contacts.
- Customers module: profiles, booking history, VIP tagging, notes.
Exit: ops can take a paid booking, assign a supplier, mark it confirmed, and track it to completion.

⸻

Sprint 6 — Notifications, Refunds, Incidents

Goal: close the operational loop.
- Notifications module: templates, Redis queue, retry logic, delivery logs; email provider + WhatsApp Business API (A-002); booking confirmation, payment confirmation, supplier confirmation, reminder, review request.
- Refunds module: refunds + history, cancellation_policies, admin → finance approval flow, Stripe refund + partial refund, customer notification.
- Incidents module (basic): incidents, updates, assignments, severity; manual creation from a booking.
- Manage Booking page: view, request modification/cancellation, contact support.
Exit: full happy path + cancellation/refund path works with notifications; incidents can be logged.

⸻

Sprint 7 — SEO Depth & Programmatic Pages

Goal: turn on the growth engine.
- Programmatic SEO: airport+service pages, service pages, guide/FAQ page templates; schema_blocks, FAQ schema, breadcrumb schema, hreflang.
- XML sitemap auto-generation + robots.txt; sitemap_logs; cache invalidation on publish.
- Internal linking; direct-answer + FAQ + AI-summary blocks on all key pages.
- Help center / FAQ pages; For Business page; service landing pages.
Exit: published airports automatically generate full SEO/AEO/AGO-optimised page sets.

⸻

Sprint 8 — AI SEO & Translation Draft Systems

Goal: scale content production without compromising quality.
- AI SEO Engine: OpenAI integration, ai_prompt_templates (versioned), ai_generation_logs, draft generation for descriptions/metadata/FAQs/schema/summaries/guides.
- AI Translation Engine: translation_jobs, AI draft → review → approve → publish, versioning, manual override.
- Admin UI: review/edit/approve queues feeding content_approval_workflow. AI never auto-publishes (D-005).
- Flight Data module: flight lookup + status, flight_data_cache, monitor jobs, delay notification.
Exit: content team generates AI drafts, reviews, and publishes; bookings show live flight status.

⸻

Sprint 9 — Hardening & Launch Readiness

Goal: production-grade quality.
- Security pass: rate limiting, input validation audit, RBAC matrix verification, webhook security, manage-token security, audit-log coverage.
- Analytics: search/booking/conversion event tracking, core admin reports (revenue by airport/service, conversion, refund rate).
- Performance: Core Web Vitals, caching, query/index review.
- QA: end-to-end tests across booking, payment, refund, publish flows; staging UAT.
- Compliance: terms, privacy, cookie consent, data retention controls.
Exit: MVP is launch-ready for the first airports.

